# {{lb|en|obsolete}}
## {{lb|en|uncountable}} The [[manner#Noun|manner]] or [[process#Noun|process]] of [[treat#Verb|treating]] someone or something; [[treatment]]; also, the manner in which someone or something [[act#Verb|acts]] or [[behave]]s; [[behaviour]].
##* {{RQ:Jonson New Inne|scene=iii|page=35|passage=''Hoſ''[''t'']. They call me Good-ſtock. / ''Lov''[''el'']. Sir, and you confeſſe it, / Both i'your language, '''treaty''', and your bearing.}}
## {{lb|en|uncountable}} The [[address#Verb|addressing]] or [[consideration]] of a [[subject#Noun|subject]]; discussion, treatment.
## {{lb|en|countable}} A [[formal#Adjective|formal]], [[systematic#Adjective|systematic]] [[discourse#Noun|discourse]] on some subject; a [[treatise]].
##* {{RQ:Browne Pseudodoxia Epidemica|chapter=Of the Second Cause of Popular Errors; the Erroneous Disposition of the People|page=7|passage=And though {{w|Galen}} doth ſometime nibble at [[w:Moses|Moſes]], and beſide the Apoſtate Chriſtian, ſome Heathens have queſtioned his Philoſophicall part or '''treaty''' of the Creation: Yet is there ſurely no reaſonable Pagan, that will not admire the rationall and well grounded precepts of Chriſt; {{...}}}}
##* {{RQ:Burnet History|volume=I|page=326|passage=The Miniſters in ''Holland'' did upon this occaſion ſhew a very particular violence. In their ſermons, and in ſome printed '''treaties''', they charged the Judges with corruption, who had carried the ſentence no farther than to baniſhment: And compared the fate of the ''De Wits'' to ''{{w|Haman}}''’s.}}
## {{lb|en|countable}} An [[act#Noun|act]] of [[beseeching#Noun|beseeeching]] or [[entreating#Noun|entreating]]; an [[entreaty]], a [[plea#Noun|plea]], a [[request#Noun|request]].
##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Antony|act=III|scene=xi|page=356|column=1|passage=Now I must / To the young man ſend humble '''Treaties''', dodge / And palter in the ſhifts of lovvnes, vvho / VVith halfe the bulke o' th' vvorld plaid as I pleas'd, / Making, and marring Fortunes.}}

